Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. It was this desire that refused to be fulfilled. It started when she was about 14, just getting into a teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she had determined she wanted someone rather than thing. Yet, she had felt no interest in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, gone through the awkward attempts to woo the un-woo-able, but no one appealed to her. She questioned herself often with this strange notion, trying to think of what it was that could possibly cause such a strange thing to happen with a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing good enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.
transformed_texts:
I want to work with people in need. I will study social work to help children who are hurt or not cared for well. I will also help families who have problems.

I want to be a good social worker. I care about helping people. I am honest and kind. I want to help people get along. I also want to learn more about my work so I can be good at it.

I have always wanted to help people. In school, I saw some people who did not know how to deal with their problems.  I saw some people use bad ways to deal with things. I got a degree in psychology to help people. 

One summer, a friend asked me to meet a boy. He was scared. He was running away from his parents because they hurt him. I talked to the police and the boy’s parents. I wanted to help. I learned that the boy needed help. I want to help children like him.

I also want to help people who are treated unfairly. It is important to treat everyone well. I believe in fairness for everyone.

I have always fought for what is right. I have done things that show I care about fairness.

This paper looks at how we understand the sleep problem called insomnia.  We look at two ways to explain insomnia: the body and the environment.  

The body way looks at genes and health problems. The environment way looks at things like where a person lives, their family, and money.

We look at studies about insomnia and how they fit with these two ways of thinking. We also talk about the good and bad parts of each study.

Sleep problems can be caused by many things.  Sometimes they are the main problem. Sometimes they are part of another problem, like a mental health problem. Sometimes they are caused by a medical problem or medicines.

There are many types of sleep problems. Some make it hard to fall asleep or stay asleep. These are called dyssomnias. Others cause strange things to happen during sleep. These are called parasomnias.

This paper focuses on insomnia and how it can be explained by the body and environment.

The body way looks at how our brains work. Parts of the brain control sleep.  One part is called the hypothalamus. It has special cells that make us sleepy or wakeful.

One study looked at mice. It found that special cells in the brain have something called GABAB receptors. These receptors help control sleep. When they are active, they make us sleepy. When they are not active, we may have trouble sleeping. This means that our genes, which control these receptors, can make a big difference in how well we sleep.

The environment way looks at things like where we live, our family, and our money. These things can all affect how well we sleep.

This paper talk about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it give a short look at the disorder. Next, it say how doctors find the disorder. Finally, the paper look at how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is when the brain has trouble using sound. The brain can hear, but it has trouble understanding sound. People with CAPD are not deaf. The part of the brain that changes sound into words and understands speech has a hard time working. 

The first time people talked about CAPD was in the 1950s. They called it “auditory imperception.” Doctors were looking at children who had trouble talking. In 1954, doctors in Italy made tests for these children.  In 1961, a doctor named Kimura made tests to see how the brain works with sound.

CAPD can show up in many ways. A person with CAPD may not hear sounds well in space. They may have trouble telling two sounds apart. They may not know sound patterns. They may not hear changes in someone's voice. They may not hear one sound because another sound is louder. They may not be able to put sound clues together to understand what is happening. They may not know the order of sounds.

To find CAPD, a doctor looks at how a person listens. They may use tests to see how well a person hears. Doctors use many tests to see if someone has CAPD. There is no one test that always works. There is no known cause for CAPD.

Twelfth Night show that hiding the truth is good for making people think something wrong. But hiding the truth for too long can make a person lose who they are. It is hard to end a lie because people may feel angry.  One must choose between keeping safe or keeping friends. Some people will not mind being tricked. But some will be hurt. 

Hiding one's real gender is a big problem. It asks why a person wants to be someone else. Viola hides to be safe.  She says, “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” . This shows Viola wants to protect herself.

Hiding as a man helps Viola, but it also makes her lonely. She is not with other women. Also, Olivia thinks Viola is a man named Sebastian and falls in love with her. Olivia says, “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” 

Viola also feels love for Orsino. He says, "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me."

Twelfth Night shows how hiding the truth can make people feel things they do not know. Olivia and Orsino may have feelings they do not understand. Maybe Olivia likes Cesario because she thinks Cesario is a man. 

Olivia changes her love quickly. She loves Cesario and then Sebastian. Olivia sees Cesario/Viola as a sister, not a lover. Olivia says, "A sister, you are she.”

German rulers were bad to people in their colonies.  This is true for the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. They were hurt very much.  But not all parts of the German colonies were the same. Some places had good schools.

In German East Africa, the British found many Africans who could read and write when they took over in 1919.  In Kamerun, and other places, people said the German schools were good.

South West Africa was very different. In East Africa, the German government built schools and taught the Africans. But in South West Africa, the church taught most of the Africans. The government gave very little help. The government did help white people learn. They built schools for them and helped the church schools.

This made a big difference in South West Africa. While other places had many Africans who could read and write, most Africans in South West Africa could not. 

There are many books about learning in German colonies. Most are in German and are old. They talk about how schools worked. Later, people wrote in English and compared schools in different colonies. They saw big differences.

One book talks about South West Africa and East Africa. The author says that many white people living in South West Africa made its schools different.


South West Africa was not as hot as other places. Many white people lived there. By 1913, there were almost 15,000 white people. That was more than any other German colony except East Africa.

Popular music has many kinds. It is hard to name them all. Many kinds of music have smaller kinds, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk. Heavy metal is one kind of rock that is very big now. It is big because it has many sounds and feels.

Heavy metal music is sad and strong. It is loud and fast. People play the instruments very well.  

Heavy metal started a long time ago. Some people say the Beatles made one of the first heavy metal songs. It was called "Helter Skelter." The song is loud and has a sad feeling.

Now there are many kinds of heavy metal. It is hard to say what heavy metal really is. It has changed a lot.

Henri Rousseau was a painter. He made special dreamlike art. Before artists like the Surrealists, he painted his own dreams.  His painting The Dream shows a woman in a dream world. It also shows Rousseau’s own dreams. He wanted to be a famous painter. 

Rousseau wanted other people to like his art.  He had a hard time. He wanted to be accepted by the art world. He had to decide if he should paint like other artists or be different. The Dream shows this problem.

Rousseau was born in France in 1844. He did not go to art school. He worked for the government. He lost his wife and many children.  He started painting to feel better.  

Rousseau wanted to be a famous painter. He started late. Other artists were more famous. He wanted to paint in a way that people would like.  A writer named Jan Gordon said Rousseau wanted to paint in a simple way so people would accept him.

Many good people think that good things and nice things are close together. They think truth and beauty are the same. This is true. We learn many things in school or from life. But we know good things and nice things without someone teaching us. Good things and nice things try to show us what is true, not tell us what to do. We try to tell why art is good or why doing good is right. We do not try to make rules for art or good behavior.

It is hard to say exactly what is good or what is pretty. We can talk about a painting and say what colors it has or how it is made. But we cannot say why it is good art. We might say, “There is something about it.” Art and good things cannot be fully explained. Flannery O'Connor said, "A story tells us things we cannot say any other way." We can talk about art, but there is still something special we cannot explain.

Good things and art are both special because we feel them deeply. We feel them in a way we cannot explain. This is true for art, especially stories. Stories are about good and bad things. They are important because they show us what is good and bad in life.

Germany is a strong country. It has good culture. Culture is in Germany from the mountains to the sea. It is from Cologne to Dresden. Germany has many parts, many tribes. 

Germany comes from many places. The name Germany is old. People do not know where it came from. One man, Tacitus, said the name came from a tribe called the Tungrians. They were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine. They fought the Gauls. Julius Caesar used the word “Germanus”. He used it to talk about the people he fought. He used it because he wanted to know who he had beaten and who he had not. 

Tacitus wrote a book about the Germans. He said the Germans were different from other people. They were not mixed with other races.

The Romans did not like the Germans. They fought with them. They took things from the Germans. Some Germans fought for Rome.

I look at the bowl.  My mind is quiet. I see the bowl.  I think about the bowl.

An artist told me to draw a box around what I see. It helps me to see the shape. I want to draw a picture like the artists I like. 

Picasso used blue. Monet liked green.  I want to draw brown. 

I pick up my brush. My hand moves. I want to make a picture.

Water falls.  Small things move in the water. 

I try to flush the toilet. It does not work.  I flush again. It still does not work.

I clean the bathroom. I wear a tie. I feel bad. Someone made a mess. I clean the mess.

Young people die in car crashes.  Many things cause this problem. The National Institutes of Health say that young brains are not ready for driving. Young drivers are also not very experienced. This makes them have more crashes, roll over more, go too fast, and drive off the road.

Young people also have more crashes when they drive with friends.  The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center did a study. They found that the more friends in the car, the more likely a crash was to happen.

Some states make young drivers get a special license. This license has rules. They can only drive for a few hours each day. They also can not have other young people in the car.

But these special licenses are not enough. Young drivers are not good at driving.  A doctor, Marvin Zuckerman, says 18 is too young to drive. He says young people like to take risks. They want to feel excited. It is better to wait until they are older to drive.

If we keep letting young people drive, more people will die.  Many more young drivers will be on the road soon. We need to make new laws about driving.

One law could be that no one under 18 can drive.  Schools can still teach kids about driving. They can get a special permit to practice before they get a real license. They will still need to practice with an adult.  

We need a law like this in every state.

I saw many old films made by Edison. I looked at the trick films. There were fifteen of them from 1895 to 1901. These films use special editing to make things look like magic. I wrote about how the films look and how some of the later films are different.

Most trick films are made inside. The camera stays in one place. This is like a stage. The actors move side to side, but not forward or back. For example, in the film “Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel,” the actors move from right to left.

The camera does not move in the films. This means the shots are long or medium. The camera does not get close to the actors. This is like in the theater, where you see the whole stage.

Most trick films are made in one shot. This means they are short. They are like a magic trick, not a story. However, one shot can be many parts put together to make the magic trick. In the film “The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots,” you can see how the film is made.

John Taylor was a strong supporter of the Republican Party. He liked the idea of people being in charge of their own lives. He worked on a farm and was in politics for a short time. This made him a well-known person who spoke out for people's freedoms.

He liked farming very much. He thought it was the best way to live. People should be allowed to farm their own land, he said. This belief made him think about how the government should work. He wanted a government that protected people's rights and did not control them too much.

He thought the United States had a chance to make a good government because it was a new country. There were no old traditions to get in the way. He believed in people's rights, like the right to be free and to own property. He said that if one right is taken away, all the rights are in danger.

Taylor thought the government should be honest and fair. He said that people are both good and bad. The government should help people be good and stop them from being bad. He said that people like having their own things and making money. But the government should make sure that people do not take advantage of each other.

Like other Republicans, Taylor wanted the government to follow the Constitution carefully. He wanted a small government that did not have too much power. He thought a big government would be too expensive and could become mean. He also said that the government should not just read the Constitution but understand what it meant. He thought the Declaration of Independence was more important because it said that the states were free and independent.

This report looks at the numbers from Figure 17. The number of commuter log reports went down a lot in the third month. This was sad news. It is hard to know why this happened. 

It was winter in New England. Fewer people walk or bike to school. Maybe this is why some reports went down. December is the end of the fall school term. People are busy with schoolwork and grades. They may not have time for the log. Also, December is the start of the holidays. Students and teachers have a break. They do not need to come to school. Classes start again in late January. This might be why there were few reports in January. But this does not explain why there were few reports in February.

New projects often start with a lot of excitement. This excitement can go down. To keep people interested, we had the Carpool Challenge Week in March. This was a special event to make people more happy to use the log. This did help get more reports.

One problem was keeping the project going. People

like to drive. This is common in our culture. We need to give people good reasons to use other ways to get around. We gave prizes like gift cards. It would be good to know if bigger prizes would help.  Things like a bike, a car that uses less gas, or an electric car might help.

The prizes stayed the same during the project. If the prizes got better during the project, it might have helped. The gift cards were good at the start. But if we had said in December that we would give away bikes, and then in January a car that uses less gas or an electric car, more people might have used the log.

An ETF is like a basket of stocks. It goes up and down with the prices of the stocks inside.  It is easy to buy and sell, like a single stock. ETFs cost less to own than some other kinds of investments. But you must pay a fee each time you buy or sell an ETF.

There are many different kinds of ETFs. Some track a list of stocks, like the S&P 500. Others track things like gold or oil.

This paper looks at one ETF called IHF. We will compare IHF to the ten biggest stocks inside it. We want to know if buying IHF is better than buying those ten stocks directly. 

To make the comparison easier, we only look at the ten biggest stocks in IHF. These stocks make up most of the money in the ETF.

We can use these stocks to guess how well IHF will do. We look at how much each stock goes up and down. This is called “beta.” We also look at how much money each stock makes.

The results show that the ten stocks make more money than IHF. They also have less risk.

But we need to know for sure if these differences are big. We can use a test to see if the differences are real or just by chance.

Edgar Allan Poe say “Dream-Land” is one of his good poems. In “Dream-Land,” Poe use the word “Thulé.”  Mabbott say Poe get this word from Virgil. Virgil use this word for a place north of Britain. The Greeks think Thulé is the end of the world. Virgil did use the word, but Poe also like German writers. 

One writer is Goethe. Poe like Goethe’s work. Karl J. Arndt say Poe copy Goethe’s poem. Arndt write about this in his book, “Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon.”

The Oxford Companion to English Literature say Goethe write a famous play called “Faust.” The first part come out in 1808, and the second part come out in 1832, when Goethe die.  In the second part of “Faust” is a short poem called “The King of Thulé.” This poem is about a king. His wife give him a cup. She die after this.  He drink a lot and cry. He want to die. He give his things to his children. He keep the cup. He go to a cliff, throw the cup in the sea, close his eyes, and die.  

The king in “The King of Thulé” is like the king in “Dream-Land.” They are sad and drink too much. “Faust” was made into a play by H P Grattan. This was less than one year before Poe use the word “Thulé” in “The Pit and the Pendulum.”


Poe use the word “Thulé” two times in his writing. Once in “The Pit and the Pendulum,” and twice in “Dream-Land.”  “The King of Thulé” and “Dream-Land” are like friends. 

The speaker in “Dream-Land” talk about Thulé. He say it is dark and lonely. He see his dead friends. He see a world without color. The king in “The King of Thulé” is sad and lonely. He lose his wife. He lose hope. The whole poem is like the speaker is in “The King of Thulé.”

Goethe was a big writer. Poe know about him, even if it was just because he like Tennyson. Poe said he like Tennyson.  Poe also know about Goethe because many people made copies of his work.

A customer was hurt in a store in California. The customer fell on applesauce. The customer wants extra money from the store. The customer says the store manager was mean. The manager knew about the applesauce but did not clean it. The manager was eating dinner.  

A judge will likely not throw out the case. To get extra money, the customer must show the manager was mean and did not care if people got hurt. The customer can say the manager knew people could fall and still did not clean it.  

On October 13, 2009, two workers told the manager about the applesauce. The manager did not want to help.  At 5:30 pm, the customer fell and hurt her back. This was not the first time someone fell in the store.

The customer wants money for her hurt and extra money for the manager’s mean actions. In California, extra money can be given if the store was bad on purpose.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam. We talked a lot about if Islam is a bad religion. This is still a big question today. After 9/11, the news showed Islam in a bad way. Now, people are more nice to Muslims. A president named Obama, who has Muslim family, could not have run for office in 2001.  

I read about the life of Muhammad. It is interesting. I thought Muhammad was mean and forced people to be Muslim. I thought he took over groups and made them follow him. But the book says he was kind and people came to him on their own.

Some things about Muhammad are like Jesus. For example, Muhammad made food multiply.  This makes Muhammad look good. But it makes Jesus look less good. It is like they are copying Jesus.  

The book gives stories about how people became Muslim. But the stories come from people who heard from other people. This makes the stories not as strong.  

The book makes Muhammad look good. But history says he was not kind. I wonder if Muslims know the real story about Muhammad.

Major ideas about Jesus and his life changed after he died.  Many ideas were added to the religion over time. This made the religion different from its start. The world is changing fast.  Many people want new ideas. Some people hold onto old ways.  But, more people want to know the real ideas of Jesus. They will study the old ideas and try to know what Jesus really taught. This will take a long time. But, more people will want to follow Jesus’ teachings only.

This will happen in the United States and Europe. People will worship like they did in Jesus’ time. The church will be strong and lead the way. But, there will be less different kinds of Christians. Everyone will believe and act more alike. 

History has many examples of big changes.  Christians were once hurt by the Roman Empire. But, the Empire became Christian.  The United States changed from slavery to African-Americans in power. 

The big change in Christianity will go back to Jesus' teachings. It will take away extra ideas.  People will read Jesus’ words in a new way. They will see them as ideas, not just facts.

Where did Christianity come from? 

The start was Judaism.  Judaism has one God. People believed God gave them rules. 

The Jewish people did not all agree. They had different groups, like Sadducees and Pharisees.

The book The Jungle show how people are greedy. They only think of them. The Jungle show this in many ways.

The owners of the factories only want to make money. They do not care about the workers or the environment. The book say, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". This show the bad things the factories make. 

The owners do not care about the workers. They want them to work long hours. They do not pay the workers well. The book say, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar".

The workers are in a bad place. There are no rules to keep them safe. The workers are like slaves. The book say, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many people write stories in ways that make the reader feel a certain way about things. Some ways are better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many ways to make the reader feel things in his book, *The Great Gatsby*. Sometimes, he uses words that do not usually go together to make a feeling. Other times, he uses objects, like colors, to make a feeling.

Fitzgerald uses colors a lot to make the reader feel things. He uses gold, green, white, gray, and red/pink. He uses white and gray to make the reader think about being the same. White is good and nice, gray is old and tired.

Fitzgerald shows this at the start of the book. Daisy and Jordan always wear white. Nick wears white to Gatsby’s party. Tom wears white when he meets Myrtle. Everyone wears white. The only time people do not wear white is when Nick sees the party. Then, the colors are bright. Fitzgerald uses white and gray for simple things, like the buildings Nick sees on his way to work, or the names of people at Gatsby’s party. He uses white and gray for people and places that are not important.

After Fitzgerald uses white and gray a lot, he uses them for Daisy.  He describes Daisy as wearing white. This makes her seem like a thing Gatsby wants, not a real person. He uses white and gray to show that Daisy is not special.

San Diego is good for farming. The weather is warm and sunny. People grow many things there, like tomatoes, oranges, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people want to buy food from farms that do not use chemicals. There are many farms that do this in San Diego. They have long waiting lists. People also like to buy eggs and milk from farms that do not use chemicals. Many of these farms give tours. People can go see how food is grown. They can also hike, watch birds, and do other things.

These farms can help the government. They can make the land better for plants and animals. They can also make money from tours and teaching people about farming.

Farming without chemicals is good for the land. It helps plants and animals. But it can be more expensive.

Farming without chemicals needs more work. It takes more time to get rid of bugs and weeds without using chemicals. It also takes more time to make the soil good.

There are other things farmers can do to help plants and animals. They can plant special plants. They can move animals around in different areas. They can get rid of plants that do not belong. They can also take care of plants so they grow in the best way. All these things can cost more money.

A farmer in San Diego wants to make money and help the land. He wants to know how to do both.

The farmer lives on a piece of land near a town called Potrero. The land is 160 acres. There are many different types of plants and animals there. Some are in danger of disappearing.

The land has been used for a long time. People lived there a long time ago. Then, people raised cows and cut down trees. The farmer wants to know how to farm in a way that helps the land and makes money. He looked at farms near him to see what they do. He also looked at government programs to see if they can help.

Culture is good to know for any talk. Culture is what people believe and how they act. It is not the same for everyone. It is not easy to say all people from one country are the same.  It is not good to say all people from Japan are nice or all people from Russia are strong. 

It is better to know how culture can help or hurt a talk. When you talk to someone from a different place, you think about your own culture. You may think about how things are done in your country. 

To know another culture, you can look at its history or how people think. You should not try to change it. You should accept it and work with it. If you are not strong in the talk, it is good to be respectful of the other culture. If you go to another place to talk, be nice to the people and follow their ways.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own ways. Some companies work long hours, others work shorter hours. You can see culture in how people dress, how they talk, and how they give jobs to people. Some companies want people to help others, other companies do not.  

Values are important. They tell you why people think the way they do. If people value being polite, they will not be mean to others in a talk. If people value strong deals, they will not give up easily.

Before you talk, it is good to know about the other person and their culture. It will help you talk better.

This paper looks at two thinkers who talk about God.  St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas both say God exists. We will look at their ideas to see which is better.  We will say that they both believe in the same God, the one from the Bible. This will make it easier to compare.

Both Anselm and Aquinas say good things. But neither one gives us a full reason to believe in God.  

We will start with Anselm. He says we know God is real because we think about him. He says that God is in our minds. We can't truly think about God not existing. This is like having faith. We believe in something even if we can't see proof.

Aquinas is different. He says we can prove God exists with logic and what we can see. He gives five reasons why God must exist. He says things like the world changes, things cause other things, and there are good and bad things. All of these things point to God.

Aquinas's idea is good for telling others about God. They can understand his reasons without having to believe something they can't see.

Many years ago, a prince was born. People later called him Buddha. He left the world and found peace. His ideas made Buddhism. Theravada is one type of Buddhism. This religion is very old. It looks different now than when Buddha lived.

One example is in Sri Lanka. Monks and people do a water ceremony. This is important, even though Buddha did not talk about it.  Buddhism has changed in small and big ways.

This is because of things inside and outside Buddhism. Inside forces come from Buddhists, both monks and people. Outside forces come from people who are not Buddhists. Some forces are bad. They hurt Buddhism. Some forces are good. They do not want to hurt or help Buddhism.

Buddhists believe in three things: Buddha, his teachings, and the community of Buddhists. Buddha's teachings are in books called the Tripitaka.

The Tripitaka has three parts. The first has Buddha's words. The second has rules for monks. The third talks about what Buddhism thinks about the world.

Buddhists believe there is no soul, life is hard, and everything changes. To end these things, people must end their wanting, anger, and confusion. This brings peace.

The United States and Mexico were rivals for many years. This was from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the war between 1846 and 1848. The United States won. It got Texas and land in the Southwest.

There were other fights between the two countries. The fights ended before World War One. The rivalry started because of different ideas about religion, culture, and way of life. These ideas caused big problems.

Many countries that share a border have problems like this. It is hard to get along when you want different things. The United States and Mexico are like this.

The United States and Mexico also had problems because of religion. This has been a problem for many countries. People in the United States did not like Catholicism and the way kings and queens ruled.

The United States had a big rivalry with the Soviet Union. This was also about ideas. But with Mexico, it was about religion.

The United States and Mexico did not trust each other because of what happened between England and Spain. They did not want to be friends.

There were many fights between the United States and Mexico. Most were about land. 

Mexico was poor. It needed help from the United States. This helped to end the rivalry.

Fifteen years ago, I became sick. The illness was new to me. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted to be safe. People always need nurses. So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or a writer, I became a nurse.

When I was 46, I could not work. I was alone and had no money. I am still sick. After 15 years of getting money from the government, I have nothing. Each day is hard. I worry about money, safety, and my pride. My life is not sure. But I know one thing: I could not have done this without help. My family and friends helped me. When bad things happen, you need help.

Emergencies happen to everyone. We can plan, but some things are too big to face alone.

I agree that we should not rely only on the government. It is not working. But I think we should help each other. We should learn to trust each other again.

Some people say America was built on being strong and independent. But our ancestors survived because they were kind to each other. They shared things and helped each other. People who traveled west in wagons did not make it alone.

So, be ready for bad times. I am. I have supplies for emergencies: food, water, light, and tools. If you have land, grow your own food.

But also, talk to your neighbors.

We want to know why things in nature change the way they do.  Are there rules that tell how they change?  A scientist named D’Arcy Thompson said this a long time ago:  "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms." This is still true today. Now, we use math to study how shells grow and change.

We are studying a type of shell called Prunum. We are using math to see how shells grow and change over time. We take pictures of the shells and use a computer program to make models. This helps us understand how shells change over time.


A shell is like a tube that spins around. Each spin is called a whorl.  Whorls go around a center line called the columella.  The whorls can grow at different speeds.  There is a line between each whorl called a suture. 

The biggest whorl is the last whorl.  All the whorls except the last one make up the spire. The spire point is the apex. The opposite end is the base. The animal lives inside the shell and comes out through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways.  We can look at the top, the bottom, the opening, or the side.  

We count the whorls by looking at the shell from the top. We draw a line to divide the shell in half. We count the whorls from that line.

We can think of a shell as a series of openings that move through time and space as the animal grows. We can use math to track the path of the opening.

Indonesia need better care for babies and mothers. The death rate for babies and new mothers is not going down fast enough. Indonesia wants to reach its goals by 2015.  But, it needs to make big changes. 

More babies now have a helper at birth. But, many helpers are not doctors. They can not help if there are problems. More kids get help for sickness with doctors. But, not enough mothers get help after they have a baby.

Many babies are born in cities. But, there are not many doctors in small towns. Poor people have trouble getting help.

Indonesia needs to decide how to make things better. Should they focus on one help program, or make the whole health system better? Programs are easier to start and help fast. But, they can take money from other programs. 

Many programs can make work hard and confusing.

Victorian books are known for details about rich people in that time. Two books that are from that time but are different are *Oliver Twist* and *Wuthering Heights*. Both books have mystery and strange parts, which is not common in books from that time. This makes the people in the books more interesting. It makes us understand why they do things and how they feel.

One part from *Oliver Twist* is:
“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.”
(Dickens, 220)

Both books use mystery a lot through dreams or dreamlike parts, but they do this in different ways. In *Oliver Twist*, these strange parts show us what is inside Oliver. They show us what hurts him and how he feels about what is happening around him. When Oliver is shot, he remembers it again in chapter 28, like a dream. This helps him try to find help. This part shows that Oliver had no control over what happened. His health was very bad. He is also seeing Sikes and Crackit, which makes him scared. The shooting is too much for him. He can’t feel his senses. He does not see the “unseen hand” that takes him away. He feels sad again, but this time it is linked to fear, not surprise. Because Oliver is so overwhelmed, we wonder who is to blame for his bad luck. It was not his own fault. This shooting shows that Oliver has no control. He cannot even try to control what is happening, even when his life is in danger. We also see that Oliver is giving up. This is because Fagin is making him sad and making him accept this sadness. If Oliver was not so sad, he would at least try to do something, even just to save his own life.

One part from *Wuthering Heights* is:
“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours.”

A few years ago, I worked with young children after school. I helped them with school work. I was good at English and reading. One boy, Adrian, had a hard time reading. He was in third or fourth grade. I helped him, but he had strange problems. He read some letters well, but others not at all. This was very strange. 

Adrian spoke English well. His parents were from Latin America. One day, Adrian's mother came to the school. She did not speak English. I spoke a little Spanish. We talked, and I understood. Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet well. I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story about the language problem in schools. Sometimes, it is not easy to see. Even if a child speaks English well, reading can be hard. We all agree this is a problem. What can we do?

For Adrian, the answer was simple: I helped him read English, especially the alphabet. But for children who do not speak English well, it is harder.

There is no one answer. We can use many things: dual language programs, immersion programs, tutors, and ESL classes. We need to use all of these.

Dual language programs are good for all children. They help children learn two languages. They also learn better in school. Some people think this wastes money, but this is not true. If we use dual language programs more, all children will benefit. We do not need all teachers to be bilingual, but we need bilingual helpers.

Many people learn about big things, things bigger than them. Some go to church, some go to temple, some look inside. Some take the beliefs of their parents. Some say there is no big thing. Some choose beliefs and then change.  We all look for meaning. We look for light in the darkness.

My father liked cardinals, he said. We sat on the porch. Rain fell on the roof. He looked at the rain. He was thin, his clothes did not fit. His hair was thin. He did not look at me. I felt sad. I was afraid to talk about missing him. I hugged him. We sat in the rain.

My father died in December. He was sick. He died five days after my birthday. He was sick for a long time. I did not know why God did this. I did not pray. I thought God did not listen.

I did not want to watch him die. I stayed away. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not how he died. I knew him best. I knew he did not want me to watch. I stayed in bed for three days. No one called.

The Gothic story is old and new. It is like a mix of ideas. Some say it is not good. Some say it is very good. It shows a feeling of fear and awe. The first Gothic story was by Horace Walpole. It was called The Castle of Otranto. He used old ways of telling stories and new ways to write about people's feelings. 

The word "Gothic" meant many things. It was old and not as good as what was new. But the Gothic story was new. It used ideas from old times and new ways of writing. This makes the Gothic story last a long time. People read it and think it is old and new at the same time.

One idea in Gothic stories is chivalry. Chivalry is about knights. They were brave and good. Gothic writers liked this idea because they felt people were not so brave and good anymore. They used chivalry to show what they wanted people to be like.  

Horace Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto when things were hard in his country. He felt people were not so good anymore. He showed this in his story. One character is named Frederic. He is like a knight. He is brave and strong.

Supply chain work is how we move things. First, we take a customer order. Then, we get the things to make the product. Next, we make the product. Then, we send the product to the customer. We call this a supply chain.

A man named Keith Oliver made up the word "supply chain management" in 1982. He said it is good to plan, do, and check the work of the supply chain so customers get things quickly and well. 

There are six parts to a supply chain: make, get, keep, place, move, and talk. These parts help make customers happy.

First, we make the product. This is very important. We need to know what the customer wants. We look at the market to see what people want. Then we decide what to make and how much. We also need to decide where to make it. We want to make it in a place that is good for making the product and good for the customer. We also need to plan when to make things and keep the machines working well. Making things right is very important.

The next part is getting the things we need to make the product. We need to decide which parts to make ourselves and which parts to get from other companies. This is called outsourcing. We do this to make things faster and cheaper.

A sign say, “Hitler is alive in Burma.” Ellen Page, star of the movie Juno, hold a sign. She stand on a street corner. Burma is a country in southeast Asia. A bad group rules Burma.  They took over in 1962.

In 2007, people in Burma have protests. Monks start the protests. They wear yellow robes. The protests are called “The Saffron Revolution.” At first, the government let the monks have small meetings. But then, things get bad. The army hurt people. They go into places where monks live. People from other countries try to take pictures. Some people get hurt or go to jail. Some people say many more people died than the government say. 

This is not new. Many years ago, Roman leaders said they were gods. They were in charge of everything.  The leader of Japan is also a god, they say.

People in China want to change things. In 1989, they have a big protest in Tiananmen Square. The government hurt many people.

In Rwanda, people hurt each other. Many people died. Hitler was bad to Jewish people. He made them leave their homes and he hurt them.

Duke Ellington is good at jazz music. He played piano and made music for many years. He was good at making music for his band. Ellington made music that was new and interesting. He made music that showed how good each band member was.  He made music where singers could play like instruments.  He made music that sounded good together. Ellington made some of the best jazz music ever. 

One song Ellington made is called Creole Love Call. It has a voice and music. The voice is like an instrument.  The voice starts slow and then gets strong. There is also a trumpet that plays a long, slow song. Then a clarinet plays fast. Then the whole band plays together.  The voice plays again, but this time it sounds rough. Last, there is a loud end.  

Ellington liked to use the voice in his music. He used it in many songs.  In the song Hot and Bothered, a trumpet player and a singer play back and forth. The trumpet sounds like a voice, and the singer sounds like a trumpet. In the song It Don’t Mean a Thing, a trombone player plays the first part of the song.

She want something. This want was strong. It start when she was fourteen years old. She was a teenager. This want was still there three years later, when she was seventeen. Now, she want a person, not a thing. But she did not want a boy. Some boys like her. They try to talk to her. But no one was good enough. She think about this a lot. What make a girl want this way? She think about many things. But nothing was right. So she live her life and wonder about her want.

Her home was usually calm. Her parents were good and quiet. They never fight. They rarely fight with her too. The only time they fight is when she want to do her own things. She is the daughter of quiet people. But she is fun and like people.

Today was not a calm day. She walk around her house. She want to find something to do. Then she hear a small scream. It was her mother, in the kitchen. She run to the kitchen. She ask, “Mom? Mom, what is wrong?” Her mother was on the floor. She say “Ow” with short breaths. The daughter help her mother. “Ouch, sweet - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital.” Her mother speak fast. The daughter know she is in a lot of pain. “Okay Mom, tell me where I should take you.” Her mother point. The daughter was happy she was strong. She help her mother to the car. She put her mother in the back seat. Then she drive to the hospital.

The hospital smell bad. It smell like sickness. But she did not think about that. She think only about her mother. She carry her mother in quickly. She call for help. Some doctors come. They put her mother on a bed. The doctors take her mother away. The daughter sit and wait.

Her mother fall off a step stool. She try to get a vase from a high shelf.

This study looked at the link between a special diet and heart health. The diet is called the “Mediterranean Diet”. People who ate more foods from this diet had less chance of heart problems.

The study used a special score to show how well people followed the diet. The score is called the “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”.  The aMed diet has lots of plants, like fruits, nuts, and beans. It has good fats and fish. It has less meat and unhealthy fats.

Before, studies showed that the Mediterranean Diet was good for health. But this study looked only at heart problems and death from heart problems.

The study followed 74,886 women for 20 years. The women answered questions about what they ate. The study looked at if they had heart problems or died from them.

The study found that women who ate more like the Mediterranean Diet had a lower chance of heart problems.

In 2007, people in the United States had much less money. Many people lost their jobs. Houses were not worth as much money. Many big companies lost money. This bad time was hard for many people.

The bad time began many years before. People in charge of the government made choices that helped banks lend money to people who could not pay back the money. The banks gave out many loans. The loans were bad.

The government helped companies that gave out the bad loans. These companies were Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac. They took the bad loans and sold them to other people. When people could not pay back the loans, the companies lost money. They could not pay back the people who had bought the loans.

Many people lost money because of the bad loans. People were afraid to lend or spend money. The bad time got worse.

People had new ways to borrow money for houses. The loans had different rules. Some loans had a higher price later. These new loans were hard to understand.

Many people took out loans for houses. They spent too much money. The prices of houses went up too high.

When the prices of houses went down, many people lost money. The banks lost money too. Many banks closed.

The government tried to help the banks. The government gave the banks money. The government took control of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.

Exposition is a tricky part of writing.  It can be boring if done wrong.

Imagine telling a story like a movie.  In a movie, sometimes a character tells another a lot of information all at once.  That can be dull.

In stories, the author sometimes does this telling instead of showing.  It's like saying, "The heroine met her husband, they got married, and then he died."  

But that's not very interesting!  We want to know how they met, what their marriage was like, and how the heroine feels about her husband.  

Think about it this way: if you were told someone loved  chocolate, you wouldn't know much about them.  But if you saw them excitedly describing the different types of chocolate they like, you'd learn more about them.

The same goes for stories.  Show us the details!

For example, instead of saying "He was a kind man," show us him helping someone in need.  Instead of saying "She was sad," show us her tears or her quiet voice.

I saw two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. The first was NBC 4. It was a live show (August 13, 2011). The first story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio. He hurt his wife.  The man's name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture. He looked bad. They talked about the story for two minutes. They said he hurt his wife many times. He was arrested.

The next story was about a young man named Travis Buyers. He was 18 years old. He was hurt by a gun early in the morning. The police are looking for who did it. They did not find anyone yet.  The police team SWAT is looking into this.

The next story was about a hole in a helicopter. They said a small gun shot hit the helicopter. The police want help finding who shot at the helicopter. They will give five thousand dollars for help.

The next story was about the weather. It will rain this weekend. It will be hot. The news wants you to watch more.
